Asked whether he would feel fulfilled if ordered to kick so often, Ford said: ‘It was obviously Ireland’s plan. If they come in with a plan and execute it as well as they did and come out with a 10-point win, then you would (feel fulfilled). You don’t always have to play the same way against different teams.

‘You go into a game with a plan and if it comes off at the weekend, you feel you’ve done your job.’

But surely he gains more satisfaction from conjuring tries than kicking for territory? ‘People always like to score tries,’ he added. ‘They are more exciting. But they are difficult to get in international rugby.

‘It’s about small margins, little things; your kicking being on the money, your set-piece and breakdown being strong.

